íŸ@aa2fe71db11eb5c976a02e8871f4272695a0ec8f6189b4e44eb9be9aa21cd6b7⁄Title: title: print
Path: Examples
Content:
Print 'hello world'
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> print "hello world"


```
Print the sum of 2 and 3
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> print (2 + 3)


```
Print 'ABC' from binary data
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> 0x[41 42 43] | print --raw


```
íŸ@85dffeda73cc4fd876510155c7be46c19091c06a0648aa7b056085380f8e4518⁄ÔTitle: title: print
Path: Notes
Content:
Unlike 
``echo``
, this command does not return any value (
``print | describe``
 will return "nothing").

Since this command has no output, there is no point in piping it with other commands.
``print``
 may be used inside blocks of code (e.g.: hooks) to display text during execution without interfering with the pipeline.

In protocol modes (
``--lsp``
, 
``--mcp``
), 
``print``
 always writes to stderr to keep stdout reserved for protocol messages.
